            <h4>How to get around the city</h4>
            <p class="text-justify">Here are some ways you can get around and explore the city</p>

            <h2 class="text-justify">Trains </h2>
            <p class="text-justify">Compared to other metropolitan cities, the train system in Aucktis not quite extensive. Four main lines connect to the Britomart Train Station. The train system is relatively new; everything is spotless and modern. </p>

            <h2 class="text-justify">Ferries </h2>
            <p class="text-justify">Fullers and Sealink operate from downtown Auckland and provide routes to places like Devonport, Waiheke Island, Rangitoto, Hobsonville Point and Half Moon Bay. Ferries are one of the most scenic ways to travel around the city. </p>

            <h2 class="text-justify">Taxis</h2>
            <p class="text-justify">The primary driving services in Auckland are Corporate Cabs and Co-op Taxis. Both services are clean and reliable, with friendly drivers who will suggest more places to explore. Taxis approximately cost under $ 75 from the airport to the central business district, irrespective of the traffic. </p>

            <h2 class="text-justify">Buses </h2>
            <p class="text-justify">In Auckland, City Link buses run regularly and have stopped all around the city. Through maps, you can get an idea of the main routes. Bus services are also there, which cater to more expansive suburban areas. Try not to hop on during rush hours as the motorways can get pretty congested. </p>

            <h2 class="text-justify">Car apps </h2>
            <p class="text-justify">In Auckland, Uber and Ola are the main and the most used car apps. Both the apps offer the customers comparable pricing. </p>

            <h4>Some of the best hotels to stay in Auckland</h4>

            <h2 class="text-justify">Park Hyatt Auckland</h2>
            <p class="text-justify">The hotel is on 99 Halsey Street, Auckland, 1010, New Zealand. The hotel occupies a prime waterfront position in Wynyard Quarter and is Auckland's glossiest new luxury hotel which has been perfectly appointed for the international jet set. </p>

            <p class="text-justify">The hotel features four restaurants and bars, a day spa, a fitness centre and versatile event spaces. There are 195 spacious rooms, including 23 suites with paranomic harbour views. The decor is sleek and modern, bringing light to New Zealand's indigenous culture. </p>

            <h2 class="text-justify">The Hotel Britomart</h2>
            <p class="text-justify">The Hotel Britomart is situated on 29 Galway Street, Britomart, Auckland, 1010, New Zealand. The hotel is one of the most highly anticipated and is the precinct's crown jewel. The Landing Suites are notable and furnished with elegant interiors and three garden terraces with stunning views of the Waitemata Harbor. </p>

            <p class="text-justify">A hotel is a perfect option for travellers who want to be surrounded by the central business district's best shopping, dining, and transportation hubs. The hotel's vibrant all-day restaurant, Kingi, is another highlight. </p>

