            <p class="text-justify">The hotel QT Auckland is located on 4 Viaduct Harbor Ave, Auckland, 1010, New Zealand. The hotel opened recently after its successful outposts in Queenstown and Wellington and has become popular with tourists and local revellers because of its sprawling rooftop bar. </p>

            <p class="text-justify">The resort gives a vibe similar to The Standard and W Hotels with a Millennial-focused take on luxury. The local influencers have been engaged as collaborators to keep the guests in the loop with the city's best offers. </p>

            <h2 class="text-justify">Hotel Fitzroy</h2>
            <p class="text-justify">The hotel is located on 43 Richmond Road, Grey Lynn. Hotel Fitzroy is an excellent option for travellers seeking more of a neighbourhood vibe. The hotel is located in a heritage villa in the backstreets of Ponsonby and is within walking distance of the trendiest cafes and cocktail bars. </p>

            <p class="text-justify">The low-key, boutique atmosphere of the hotel offers an authentic look at the lives of the locals. The hotel has ten rooms, out of which two spaces are considered luxury suites. Guests are served breakfast in the room, and in the evening, drinks are provided in a social setting in the library. </p>



            <h4>Things you must do in Auckland</h4>
            <h2 class="text-justify">Visit Matakana</h2>
            <p class="text-justify">Matakana is Auckland's version of Napa Valley, dotted with vineyards and rustic al fresco. It would be best if you visited Brick Bay, a sculpture trail with contemporary installations spread throughout a serene bush path. </p>

            <p class="text-justify">During weekends, there is a Farmer's Market hosted in Matakana Village where one can buy artisan cheeses, pastries, pies, crepes and condiments. If you visit this area, then make sure to visit Omaha Beach or Tawharanui Regional Park. You can hire an Auckland travel guide to explore the city more. </p>

            <h2 class="text-justify">Auckland Art Gallery is worth visiting</h2>
            <p class="text-justify">The art gallery is the largest art institution in New Zealand. The gallery is an integral part of the city's cultural scene, and the building is an architectural delight and has received various global awards. You can currently find 17000 artworks within the collection, which includes an impressive range of historic and contemporary paintings, sculptures and prints. </p>

            <p class="text-justify">Besides showcasing local artists, the art gallery has hosted various international exhibitions, including Yayoi Kasuma's Instagram-friendly Obliteration Room'. The gallery also includes classic masterpieces from Monet, Renoir, Magritte, Van Gogh and many more. </p>

            <h2 class="text-justify">Waiheke Island</h2>
            <p class="text-justify">You can venture with your family to Waiheke Island for a day trip and explore the beautiful vineyards. You can find several places, including Tantalus Estate and Mudbrick, and Man O' War, which is accessible by boat. </p>

            <p class="text-justify">You can also visit the beautiful beaches like Oneroa, Palm Beach and Onetangi, which are the best. Making a trip to The Island Gelato Co. in Oneroa Village for a scoop of amaretto ice cream is worth it. You can also charter a helicopter and enjoy the spectacular scenery from above. </p>

            <h2 class="text-justify">Visit the La Cigale French Market</h2>
            <p class="text-justify">La Cigale French Market is one of the best places for shopping because of its atmosphere. The market bustles on the weekends with a variety of artisan vendors selling a wide selection of food, including almond croissants, paella, crepes, beef bourguignon pies, bacon and egg brioche buns. </p>

